\section{Results and Discussion}
\section{1. Binding Energies}
EDTA and CA are chelating agents that can bind to metal cations to form complexes. EDTA is a type of polyamino carboxylic acid that can bind to a metal via four carboxyl and two amine groups, meaning it has six sites with a lone pair of electrons. CA is a polydentate ligand and can bind to metals via three carboxyl groups with a lone pair of electrons at each. In this study, the binding energies of metal- $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and metal-EDTA ${ }_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ complexes were calculated in order to determine their stability.

At the level of theory B3LYP/6-31G $\mathrm{G}^{*}$ and UGBS geometry optimization, the following results were obtained: $E\left(\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}\right)=-20626.57 \mathrm{eV}, E\left(\mathrm{EDTA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}\right)=-29911.50 \mathrm{eV}$, $E\left(\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}\right)=-214598.65 \mathrm{eV}, E\left(\mathrm{Y}^{3+}\right)=-90707.64 \mathrm{eV}$, and $E\left(\mathrm{Zr}^{4+}\right)=-96342.96 \mathrm{eV}$.

The binding energies of $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and $\mathrm{EDTA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ metal complexes were calculated from equation (1) and are shown in Tables 1 and 2. A higher negative value of $E_{b}$ indicates higher stability of the complex. Table 1 shows the $E_{b}$ of metal-CA ${ }_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ complexes at five different positions of metal attachment. $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}$ attaches strongly at $\mathrm{P} 2$ and has an $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ of $-19.39 \mathrm{eV}$. Interestingly, in $\mathrm{Y}-\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$, the $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ is highest at $\mathrm{P} 4$ and $\mathrm{P} 5$ and both sites have the same $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ of $-21.82 \mathrm{eV}$. In the $\mathrm{Zr}-\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ complex, the $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ values at $\mathrm{P} 4$ and $\mathrm{P} 5$ are similar at $-24.89 \mathrm{eV}$. The highest and most stable $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ was at P3 $(-25.69 \mathrm{eV})$.

The calculated $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ values of metal-EDTA ${ }_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ complexes are tabulated in Table 2. In Ba-EDTA ${ }_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ complexes, $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}$ prefers to attach at $\mathrm{P} 2$ as this $E_{\mathrm{b}}(-26.67 \mathrm{eV})$ is the highest compared to other sites. Table 2 also shows that the $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ for P1 differs from P2 by $0.01 \mathrm{eV}$. Hence, these two sites in EDTA $_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ are favorable to $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}$ for attachment. In the Y-ED$\mathrm{TA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ and $\mathrm{Zr}-\mathrm{EDTA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ complexes, the cations bonded strongly at $\mathrm{P} 5$ and exhibited a high $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ values of $-33.12 \mathrm{eV}$ and $-37.33 \mathrm{eV}$, respectively.

