Based on Tables 1 and 2, similar $E_{\mathrm{b}}$ values are observed at $\mathrm{P} 1 / \mathrm{P} 2$ and $\mathrm{P} 4 / \mathrm{P} 5$ in $\mathrm{Y}-\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and $\mathrm{Zr}-\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ complexes. This is due to the symmetrical arrangement of the atoms in CA. However, this is not observed in $\mathrm{Ba}-\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$, potentially due to the larger size of $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}$. Similarly in the $\mathrm{Ba}-\mathrm{EDTA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ complex, it is difficult for $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}$ to reside at any other site on EDTA due to its larger size.

\section{2. Geometry Optimization}
Geometry optimizations were performed on the metal complexes using $6-31 G^{*}$ and UGBS basis sets and no imaginary frequencies were observed. The stationary point of each structure where the energy was at a minimum was therefore ascertained. ${ }^{29}$ The geometrically optimized structures of the most stable metal- $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and metal-EDTA ${ }_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ complexes formed are shown in Fig. 3 to 8 . The bond lengths between metal and $\mathrm{O}$ are discussed since $\mathrm{O}$ and $\mathrm{N}$ donate electrons and play an important role in the metal interaction.

In general, metal complexation marginally changes the shape of $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$. $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}$ was found most stable at $\mathrm{P} 2$ with bond lengths of $\mathrm{Ba}-\mathrm{O} 5=2.704 \AA, \mathrm{Ba}-\mathrm{O} 9=2.602 \AA$, and $\mathrm{Ba}-\mathrm{O} 11$ $=2.602 \AA$ (the optimized structure of $\mathrm{Ba}-\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ is shown in Fig. 3). These results concur with findings from a previous study by Makrlik et al ${ }^{30}$ where the bond length of $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}$ to oxygen atoms in the beauvericin ligand are $2.5 \sim 4.9 \AA$.

