\section{3. Mulliken Charges}
The Mulliken charges of the most stable metal- $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and metal-EDTA ${ }_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ complexes are shown in Tables 3 and 4. The initial ionic charges of $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}, \mathrm{Y}^{3+}$, and $\mathrm{Zr}^{4+}$ decrease after complexation with $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and $\mathrm{EDTA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$. The decreasing in charge can be attributed to the transfer of electrons from CA and EDTA to the metal. ${ }^{39,40}$ The charge transfer in metal complexes is of utmost important as it influences the interaction between metal and chelating agent. It can be inferred that the greater the charge reduction in the metal the stronger the interaction in the metal complex. ${ }^{41}$

