C1, C4, C6, and C7 in $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and $\mathrm{C} 17$ to $\mathrm{C} 20$ in ED$\mathrm{TA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ (shown in Tables 4 and 5) carry positive charges as they are bonded to O. O atoms have a higher electronegativity than $\mathrm{C}$ atoms, meaning an $\mathrm{O}$ bond more strongly attracts the bonding pair of electrons compared to a $C$ atom. Consequently, the electron pair is pulled towards the $\mathrm{O}$ atom, making the carbon atom positively charged. The same is observed in $\mathrm{H}$ atoms. All $\mathrm{H}$ atoms have a positive charge. H18 in $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ has a higher positive charge than other $\mathrm{H}$ atoms as it is bonded to an $\mathrm{O}$ atom. This is confirmed in a recent study by Gangadhara and Krishnan. ${ }^{43}$

\section{Conclusion}
The density functional B3LYP method was used to investigate interactions between chelating agents and metal cations in forming a specific barium zirconate (BZY) compound. The aim of the study was to determine the preferred coordinaton sites for $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}, \mathrm{Y}^{3+}$, and $\mathrm{Zr}^{4+}$ in $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and EDTA $_{4 \mathrm{H}}$. The results show that $\mathrm{CA}_{3 \mathrm{H}}$ and $\mathrm{EDTA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ can bind to the metal cations considered. The metal cations were observed to bind to the electron-rich sites of the chelating agents. Not all sites had the same binding energy, however. Moreover, different cations showed different bonding strengths. Based on the results, $\mathrm{Zr}^{4+}$ complexation was found to be the most stable compared to the other complexes. $\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}$ did not fully chelate to $\mathrm{EDTA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$, rendering $\mathrm{Ba}-$ $\mathrm{EDTA}_{4 \mathrm{H}}$ the least stable complex. The greater binding energies of EDTA, alongside its ability to bind metals through four carboxyl and two amine groups, confirm its stronger chelating power with respect to CA.

